In this Act, unless the context otherwise requires—
'access' means the ability to read, view, use, copy, modify or transfer data;
'biometric data' means personal data resulting from specific technical processing relating to the physical, physiological, or behavioural characteristics of a natural person;
'Commissioner' means the Personal Data Protection Commissioner appointed under section 47;
'consent' means any freely given, specific, informed and unambiguous indication of the data subject's wishes by which he or she, by a statement or by a clear affirmative action, signifies agreement to the processing of personal data relating to him or her;
'credit reporting business' has the same meaning assigned to it in the Credit Reporting Agencies Act 2010 [Act 710];
'credit reporting agency' has the same meaning assigned to it in the Credit Reporting Agencies Act 2010;
'data breach' means a breach of security leading to the accidental or unlawful destruction, loss, alteration, unauthorised disclosure of, or access to, personal data transmitted, stored, or otherwise processed;
'data processor' means any person, other than an employee of the data user, who processes personal data solely on behalf of the data user, and does not process the personal data for any of his own purposes;
'data protection officer' means a person appointed under section 129B to carry out the functions set out in this Act;
'data subject' means an individual who is the subject of personal data;
'data user' means a person who either alone or jointly or in common with other persons processes any personal data or has control over or authorizes the processing of any personal data, but does not include a data processor;
'document' includes summons, notice, order, and any other document required or authorized to be served under this Act;
'health data' means personal data related to the physical or mental health of a natural person, including the provision of health care services, which reveals information about his or her health status;
'Minister' means the Minister responsible for personal data protection;
'personal data' means any information in respect of commercial transactions, which—(a) is being processed wholly or partly by means of equipment operating automatically in response to instructions given for that purpose; (b) is recorded with the intention that it should be processed by means of such equipment; or (c) is recorded as part of a relevant filing system or with the intention that it should form part of a relevant filing system, that relates directly or indirectly to a data subject, who is identified or identifiable from that information or from that and other information in the possession of a data user, including any sensitive personal data and expression of opinion about the data subject;
'processing' in relation to personal data, means collecting, recording, holding or storing the personal data or carrying out any operation or set of operations on the personal data, including—(a) organization, adaptation or alteration of personal data; (b) retrieval, consultation or use of personal data; (c) disclosure of personal data by transmission, transfer, dissemination or otherwise making available; or (d) alignment, combination, correction, erasure or destruction of personal data;
'relevant filing system' means any set of information relating to individuals to the extent that, although the information is not processed by means of equipment operating automatically in response to instructions given for that purpose, the set is structured, either by reference to individuals or by reference to criteria relating to individuals, in such a way that specific information relating to a particular individual is readily accessible;
'sensitive personal data' means any personal data consisting of information as to the physical or mental health or condition of a data subject, his political opinions, his religious beliefs or other beliefs of a similar nature, the commission or alleged commission by him of any offence, or any other personal data as the Minister may determine by order published in the Gazette;
'third party' means any person other than—(a) a data subject; (b) a data user; (c) a data processor; or (d) any person authorized by the data user or data processor to process personal data.

(1) This Act does not apply to—
(a) any person who processes personal data for the purpose of, or in connection with, personal, family or household affairs (including recreational purposes);
(b) any person who processes personal data only for journalistic, literary, or academic purposes to the extent that such exemption is necessary to reconcile the right to privacy with the rules governing freedom of expression;
(c) personal data processed outside Malaysia unless that personal data is intended for further processing in Malaysia.
(2) This Act does not apply to credit reporting businesses licensed under the Credit Reporting Agencies Act 2010 [Act 710] in the carrying out of their credit reporting business.

(1) A data user shall not process personal data about a data subject unless the processing complies with the personal data protection principles.
(2) The personal data protection principles are—
(a) the General Principle;
(b) the Notice and Choice Principle;
(c) the Disclosure Principle;
(d) the Security Principle;
(e) the Retention Principle;
(f) the Data Integrity Principle; and
(g) the Access Principle.

(1) A data user shall not process personal data about a data subject unless the data subject has given his consent to the processing of the personal data.
(2) Notwithstanding subsection (1), a data user may process personal data about a data subject without the consent of the data subject if the processing is necessary—
(a) for the performance of a contract to which the data subject is a party;
(b) for the taking of steps at the request of the data subject with a view to entering into a contract;
(c) for compliance with any legal obligation to which the data user is subject, other than an obligation imposed by contract;
(d) in order to protect the vital interests of the data subject;
(e) for the administration of justice;
(f) for the exercise of any functions conferred on any person by or under any written law;
(g) for the purposes of legitimate interests pursued by the data user or by the third party or parties to whom the data is disclosed, except where the processing is unwarranted in any particular case by reason of prejudice to the rights and freedoms or legitimate interests of the data subject; or
(h) for any other circumstances as may be specified by the Minister.

(1) A data user who collects personal data about a data subject shall take such steps as are practicable to ensure that the data subject is informed before or upon collection of the personal data, or as soon as practicable after the collection, of—
(a) the data user's name and contact details;
(b) the description of the personal data collected;
(c) the purpose for which the personal data is being or is to be collected and further processed;
(d) any information regarding the disclosure of personal data—
(i) in accordance with section 8; and
(ii) if applicable, information regarding the classes of third parties to whom the data user discloses or may disclose the personal data;
(e) the data subject's right to request access to, and correction of, the personal data and how to contact the data user with any inquiries or complaints in respect of the personal data;
(f) whether it is obligatory or voluntary for the data subject to supply the personal data, and where it is obligatory, the consequences for the data subject if he fails to supply the personal data;
(g) whether the personal data will be transferred to a place outside Malaysia; and
(h) any other information as may be prescribed.
(2) Where personal data about a data subject has been collected, a data user shall, where a data subject so requests, inform the data subject whether personal data relating to the data subject is being processed by or on behalf of the data user.
(3) A data user who collects personal data directly from the data subject shall take such steps as are practicable to ensure that the data subject is aware of whether the supply of the personal data is voluntary or obligatory, and where it is obligatory, the consequences of failing to supply such data.

(1) A data user shall not disclose personal data about a data subject—
(a) for any purpose other than the purpose for which the personal data was to be disclosed at the time of collection of the personal data, or a purpose directly related to such purpose;
(b) to any party other than the party to whom the data user had informed the data subject the personal data would be disclosed;
unless the data subject has consented to a different disclosure.
(2) Notwithstanding subsection (1), a data user may disclose personal data about a data subject without the consent of the data subject if the disclosure is—
(a) necessary for the prevention or detection of crime;
(b) required for the purpose of, or in connection with, any legal proceedings, including prospective legal proceedings;
(c) necessary for the purpose of obtaining legal advice;
(d) necessary for the purpose of establishing, exercising or defending legal rights;
(e) necessary in order to prevent serious harm to any person;
(f) necessary to protect the vital interests of the data subject where consent cannot be given by or on behalf of the data subject;
(g) for the purpose of any investigation of any offence under any written law;
(h) necessary for compliance with any legal obligation of the data user;
(i) necessary for any other purpose as may be specified by the Minister.

(1) A data user shall take practical steps to protect the personal data from any loss, misuse, modification, unauthorised or accidental access or disclosure, alteration or destruction.
(2) In determining the appropriate level of security to be given to personal data under this section, a data user shall have regard to—
(a) the nature of the personal data and the harm that would result from such loss, misuse, modification, unauthorised or accidental access or disclosure, alteration or destruction;
(b) the place or location where the personal data is processed;
(c) any security measure incorporated into any equipment in which the personal data is stored;
(d) the measures taken for ensuring the reliability, integrity and competence of personnel having access to the personal data; and
(e) the measures taken for ensuring the secure transfer of the personal data.
(3) Where personal data is processed by a data processor on behalf of a data user, the data user shall—
(a) ensure processing by the data processor is governed by a written contract; and
(b) take reasonable steps to ensure that the data processor implements appropriate security measures in respect of the personal data processed.

A data user shall allow a data subject—
(a) to have access to his personal data held by the data user;
(b) to correct that personal data where the personal data is inaccurate, incomplete, misleading or not up-to-date, except where the request for such correction is refused for a reason provided under this Act.

(1) The Commissioner may suspend or cancel the registration of a data user if the data user—
(a) has ceased to process personal data;
(b) has been convicted of an offence under this Act;
(c) is no longer a fit and proper person;
(d) has breached any condition of registration;
(e) has made a false or misleading statement in his application for registration;
(f) is an undischarged bankrupt, has entered into a composition with creditors, or in the case of a body corporate, is in receivership or under judicial management;
(g) has failed to comply with an enforcement notice.
(2) The Commissioner shall, before suspending or cancelling a registration, notify the data user in writing of the grounds for the proposed action and allow the data user to make representations.
(3) The Commissioner may impose conditions upon lifting a suspension.
(4) A data user whose registration is suspended or cancelled shall, notwithstanding the suspension or cancellation, continue to comply with this Act in respect of any personal data held at the time of suspension or cancellation.

(1) A data user shall not process sensitive personal data about a data subject unless—
(a) the data subject has given his explicit consent to the processing of the sensitive personal data;
(b) the processing is necessary for the purposes of exercising or performing any right or obligation which is conferred or imposed by law on the data user in connection with employment;
(c) the processing is necessary in order to protect the vital interests of the data subject or another person, in a case where consent cannot be given by or on behalf of the data subject, or the data user cannot reasonably be expected to obtain the consent of the data subject;
(d) the processing is carried out in the course of its legitimate activities by any body or association not established or conducted for profit, and with appropriate safeguards, by a body or association—
(i) whose objects are of a political, philosophical, religious or trade-union nature; and
(ii) on condition that the processing relates solely to the members of the body or association or to persons who have regular contact with it in connection with its purposes, and that the data is not disclosed to a third party without the consent of the data subjects;
(e) the information contained in the personal data has been made public as a result of steps deliberately taken by the data subject;
(f) the processing is necessary for the purpose of, or in connection with, any legal proceedings, including prospective legal proceedings;
(g) the processing is necessary for the purpose of obtaining legal advice or for the purpose of establishing, exercising, or defending legal rights;
(h) the processing is necessary for medical purposes and is undertaken by a health professional or a person who in the circumstances owes a duty of confidentiality equivalent to that which would arise if that person were a health professional;
(i) the processing is necessary for the purpose of, or in connection with, the prevention or detection of any unlawful act and must necessarily be carried out without the consent of the data subject;
(j) the processing is necessary for the discharge of a function which is designed for protecting members of the public against dishonesty, malpractice, or other seriously improper conduct by, or the unfitness or incompetence of, any person.
(2) Subsection (1) shall apply in place of the General Principle insofar as the processing of sensitive personal data is concerned.

(1) A data user shall not transfer any personal data of a data subject to a place outside Malaysia unless to such place as specified by the Minister, by notification in the Gazette.
(2) Notwithstanding subsection (1), personal data may be transferred to a place outside Malaysia where—
(a) the data subject has consented to the transfer;
(b) the transfer is necessary for the performance of a contract between the data subject and the data user;
(c) the transfer is necessary for the conclusion or performance of a contract between the data user and a third party, entered into at the request of the data subject, and which is in the interests of the data subject;
(d) the transfer is necessary for reasons of substantial public interest;
(e) the transfer is for the purpose of legal proceedings or prospective legal proceedings;
(f) the transfer is necessary to protect the vital interests of the data subject;
(g) the personal data is in a public register;
(h) the transfer is made on terms of a kind approved by the Commissioner as ensuring adequate protection for the rights and freedoms of data subjects.

A person shall not process personal data in respect of a data subject unless he obtains that personal data directly from the data subject except—
(a) where the data subject is a minor;
(b) where the data subject lacks the legal competence to give consent;
(c) where the data subject has consented to the data being obtained from a third party;
(d) where the processing of the personal data is for the prevention or detection of crime or where required by law;
(e) where the data user could not reasonably be expected to have obtained the data directly from the data subject.

(1) If the Commissioner is satisfied that a data user has contravened or is contravening any of the data protection principles, the Commissioner may serve on the data user a notice (in this Act referred to as an 'enforcement notice') requiring the data user to take, within such time as may be specified in the notice, such steps as may be so specified for complying with the principles.
(2) An enforcement notice may require the data user—
(a) to rectify or erase the personal data;
(b) to cease processing any personal data, or any personal data of a description specified in the notice;
(c) to cease processing for a specified purpose or in a specified manner;
(d) to block access to the personal data.
(3) A data user who contravenes an enforcement notice commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable—
(a) to a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit; or
(b) to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years; or
(c) to both.

(1) A data subject has the right to request the erasure of personal data concerning him where—
(a) the personal data is no longer necessary in relation to the purposes for which it was collected or otherwise processed;
(b) the data subject withdraws consent on which the processing was based and there are no other legal grounds for processing;
(c) the data subject objects to the processing and there are no overriding legitimate grounds for the processing;
(d) the personal data has been unlawfully processed;
(e) the personal data has to be erased for compliance with a legal obligation.
(2) The data user shall, without undue delay, erase the personal data upon receiving a request under subsection (1) unless retention is required by law or for the establishment, exercise, or defence of legal claims.
(3) Where the data user has made the personal data public, it shall take reasonable steps to inform other data users processing the personal data of the data subject's request for erasure.
(4) The right to erasure shall not apply to the extent that processing is necessary for the exercise of the right of freedom of expression and information, or for compliance with a legal obligation.

(1) The Commissioner shall have the following functions:
(a) to exercise the powers conferred by this Act;
(b) to advise the Minister generally on matters relating to personal data protection;
(c) to carry out public education campaigns regarding personal data protection;
(d) to issue codes of practice in accordance with section 24;
(e) to carry out or commission research relating to personal data protection;
(f) to register data users and carry out registration-related functions;
(g) to investigate complaints received under this Act;
(h) to promote good personal data protection practices;
(i) to maintain a register of data users;
(j) to liaise and co-operate with personal data protection authorities of other countries and territories;
(k) to carry out such other functions as are conferred on the Commissioner by this Act or any other written law.
(2) The Commissioner shall report annually to the Minister on the performance of his functions and the Minister shall cause such report to be tabled before Parliament.

(1) The Commissioner shall have the powers conferred by this Act.
(2) The Commissioner may delegate any power conferred on the Commissioner by this Act, other than this power of delegation, to any officer or employee of the Department.
(3) For the purpose of discharging his functions under this Act, the Commissioner may—
(a) require any person to provide information;
(b) require any data user to provide access to any equipment or facility;
(c) issue enforcement notices;
(d) carry out audits and inspections;
(e) apply to court for an order requiring compliance with a requirement of this Act;
(f) take any other action as may be conferred by this Act.

(1) The Commissioner shall maintain a register of data users (referred to as the 'Register').
(2) The Register shall contain in respect of each data user—
(a) the name and address of the data user;
(b) a description of the personal data being or to be processed and the category or categories of data subjects to which the data relates;
(c) a description of the purpose or purposes for which the data is being or is to be processed;
(d) a description of any persons to whom the data user intends or may wish to disclose the data;
(e) whether the personal data is to be transferred to places outside Malaysia; and
(f) such other information as the Commissioner may require.
(3) The Register shall be available for inspection by the public at the office of the Commissioner and on the Commissioner's website at no charge.

(1) The Commissioner shall, as soon as practicable after the end of each calendar year, prepare and submit to the Minister a report on the activities of the Commissioner during that year.
(2) The report shall include—
(a) a summary of complaints received and investigations conducted;
(b) a summary of enforcement actions taken;
(c) statistics on data breach notifications received;
(d) details of codes of practice issued;
(e) details of data user registrations and de-registrations;
(f) any recommendations for reform of the law;
(g) any other matters that the Commissioner considers relevant.
(3) The Minister shall cause the report to be tabled before Parliament as soon as practicable.

(1) There is established a fund to be known as the Personal Data Protection Fund.
(2) The Fund shall be under the control and management of the Commissioner.
(3) The Fund shall consist of—
(a) moneys appropriated by Parliament;
(b) fees collected under this Act;
(c) fines and penalties collected under this Act;
(d) gifts, donations, or contributions from any source;
(e) interest earned on investments made from the Fund; and
(f) any other moneys lawfully received by or for the Commissioner.

(1) The Fund shall be applied to meet—
(a) the remuneration and allowances of the Commissioner and Deputy Commissioner;
(b) the salaries and allowances of officers and staff of the Commissioner;
(c) the fees and expenses of members of the Advisory Committee and Appeal Tribunal;
(d) the costs of any audit, inspection, or investigation conducted under this Act;
(e) the costs of any public education or awareness campaign;
(f) the costs of research on personal data protection;
(g) the costs of attending conferences, seminars, and training related to personal data protection;
(h) any other expenditure as may be authorized by the Minister for the purposes of this Act.

(1) There is established a committee to be known as the Personal Data Protection Advisory Committee.
(2) The Advisory Committee shall consist of—
(a) a Chairman, appointed by the Minister;
(b) the Commissioner, as an ex officio member;
(c) not less than three and not more than twelve other members appointed by the Minister.
(3) The Chairman and other members shall be persons who appear to the Minister to be qualified to advise on the processing of personal data, whether by virtue of their knowledge, experience, expertise, or interest in matters relating to personal data protection, information technology, law, consumer protection, or other relevant fields.

(1) The Advisory Committee shall have the following functions:
(a) to advise the Commissioner on matters relating to the performance of the Commissioner's functions under this Act;
(b) to advise the Minister on matters relating to personal data protection;
(c) to review and comment on proposed codes of practice before they are issued by the Commissioner;
(d) to advise on whether any class of data users should be required to register under this Act;
(e) to advise on the designation of countries for the purposes of cross-border data transfer;
(f) to carry out such other functions as are conferred on the Advisory Committee by this Act or as may be directed by the Minister.
(2) The Advisory Committee shall report to the Minister and the Commissioner on the discharge of its functions whenever requested and shall submit an annual report to the Minister.

(1) A member of the Advisory Committee shall hold office for a term not exceeding two years and shall be eligible for reappointment.
(2) A member may resign from the Advisory Committee at any time by giving not less than one month's written notice to the Minister.
(3) The Minister may at any time revoke the appointment of any member if the member—
(a) is unable to perform his functions;
(b) is declared a bankrupt;
(c) is convicted of an offence;
(d) is guilty of misconduct; or
(e) has contravened the secrecy requirements under this Act.
(4) A member who has resigned or whose appointment has been revoked shall not be entitled to any compensation in respect of the termination of his appointment.

(1) The Advisory Committee shall cause minutes of all its meetings to be kept.
(2) Minutes shall include—
(a) the names of members present;
(b) all matters deliberated;
(c) all decisions made;
(d) all disclosures of interests made under section 75.
(3) Minutes which have been confirmed by the Advisory Committee at a subsequent meeting and signed by the Chairman of that meeting shall be conclusive evidence of the facts stated therein.

The Minister may make regulations for or in respect of the Advisory Committee for all or any of the following purposes:
(a) prescribing procedures for meetings and deliberations of the Advisory Committee;
(b) prescribing the conduct and procedure of the Advisory Committee;
(c) generally for giving full effect to the functions of the Advisory Committee.

(1) The President and members of the Tribunal shall hold office for a period not exceeding three years and shall be eligible for reappointment.
(2) The President and a member may resign from office by giving not less than one month's written notice to the Minister.
(3) The Minister may terminate the appointment of the President or a member if the President or member—
(a) is unable to perform his functions due to infirmity;
(b) is declared a bankrupt;
(c) is convicted of an offence;
(d) is guilty of misconduct; or
(e) has contravened the terms and conditions of appointment.

(1) Any person who is aggrieved by—
(a) a decision of the Commissioner to refuse registration or renewal of registration;
(b) a decision of the Commissioner to cancel or suspend a registration;
(c) the service of an enforcement notice;
(d) any other decision of the Commissioner made under this Act that is specified in regulations,
may appeal to the Tribunal.
(2) An appeal must be made within thirty days of the date on which the appellant is notified of the decision being appealed.
(3) An appeal shall be made in the prescribed form and shall be accompanied by the prescribed fee.

(1) The Tribunal shall have the same power to punish for contempt as a superior court.
(2) A person commits contempt of the Tribunal if the person—
(a) disobeys an order of the Tribunal;
(b) interferes with or obstructs any proceedings of the Tribunal;
(c) publishes any matter which interferes with or obstructs the administration of justice by the Tribunal.
(3) A person who commits contempt of the Tribunal may be punished by the Tribunal with a fine not exceeding five thousand ringgit or imprisonment not exceeding six months.

(1) The Minister may make rules governing the practice and procedure of the Tribunal, including rules relating to—
(a) the form and manner of applications;
(b) the giving of notices;
(c) the conduct of hearings;
(d) the payment of fees and expenses;
(e) any other matters relating to the Tribunal's functions.
(2) Until rules are made under this section, the Tribunal may adopt such procedure as it considers appropriate.

(1) The Commissioner or any authorised officer may, for the purpose of ascertaining whether any provision of this Act is being complied with, at all reasonable times enter and inspect any premises in or at which personal data is being or is reasonably suspected of being processed.
(2) The Commissioner or authorised officer may—
(a) inspect any equipment being used for the processing of personal data;
(b) require the production of documents, records, and other materials relating to the processing of personal data;
(c) examine or take copies of any documents, records, or data;
(d) question any person on the premises who is involved in the processing of personal data;
(e) take samples of any material where necessary.
(3) The Commissioner shall, except in urgent circumstances, give reasonable notice before conducting an inspection.
(4) A person who obstructs or hinders the Commissioner or an authorised officer in the exercise of the powers under this section commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years or to both.

(1) Any person who believes that a data user has contravened or is contravening any provision of this Act may lodge a complaint with the Commissioner.
(2) A complaint shall be—
(a) in writing;
(b) signed by the complainant or the complainant's representative; and
(c) submitted in the prescribed form.
(3) The Commissioner may require the complainant to provide additional information or documentation to support the complaint.
(4) The Commissioner shall acknowledge receipt of a complaint within fourteen days and notify the complainant of the outcome of the assessment of the complaint.
(5) The Commissioner may decline to investigate a complaint if—
(a) the complaint is frivolous or vexatious;
(b) the subject matter of the complaint is not within the jurisdiction of the Commissioner;
(c) the complaint is out of time;
(d) there are other more appropriate means of resolving the matter.
(6) The Commissioner shall inform the complainant of the reasons for declining to investigate.

(1) The Commissioner may, on his own initiative or following a complaint, investigate any matter relating to compliance with this Act.
(2) In conducting an investigation, the Commissioner may—
(a) require any person to provide information;
(b) require any person to attend before the Commissioner to answer questions;
(c) inspect any equipment or premises;
(d) examine and retain any document or record;
(e) take any sample of material.
(3) A person who fails to comply with a requirement under subsection (2) commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding one hundred thousand ringgit.
(4) A person who provides false or misleading information to the Commissioner in the course of an investigation commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years or to both.

(1) A Magistrate may issue a production order requiring a person to produce any document, record, or other material relating to an offence under this Act.
(2) A production order shall specify—
(a) the documents, records, or materials required;
(b) the person required to produce them;
(c) the time and place for production.
(3) A person who fails to comply with a production order commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding one hundred thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years or to both.

Any person who—
(a) obstructs, hinders, or impedes any enforcement officer in the exercise of any power under this Act;
(b) fails to comply with any lawful requirement of an enforcement officer;
(c) uses threatening or abusive language to or assaults an enforcement officer in the performance of his duties,
commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years or to both.

(1) The Commissioner may, following an investigation, order a data user to pay a financial penalty not exceeding the maximum fine prescribed for the relevant offence.
(2) In determining the amount of the financial penalty, the Commissioner shall have regard to—
(a) the nature, gravity, and duration of the contravention;
(b) the number of data subjects affected;
(c) whether the data user has taken steps to remedy the contravention;
(d) the financial capacity of the data user;
(e) any previous contraventions by the data user;
(f) the degree of cooperation with the Commissioner's investigation;
(g) any financial benefit obtained from the contravention.
(3) A data user who is ordered to pay a financial penalty may appeal to the Tribunal.
(4) Financial penalties shall be paid into the Fund.

(1) A person who is the subject of an investigation under this Act has the right to—
(a) be informed of the nature of the investigation;
(b) be given a reasonable opportunity to make representations;
(c) be represented by an advocate and solicitor;
(d) access documents obtained by the Commissioner that the Commissioner intends to rely upon in proceedings, subject to the Commissioner's power to withhold information on public interest grounds.
(2) Nothing in this section requires the Commissioner to disclose the identity of a complainant.

(1) A data user shall not transfer personal data to a place outside Malaysia except in accordance with this section.
(2) A data user may transfer personal data to a place outside Malaysia where—
(a) the transfer is to a place that has been specified by the Minister by notification in the Gazette as providing an adequate level of protection for personal data;
(b) the data subject has given consent to the transfer;
(c) the transfer is necessary for the performance of a contract between the data subject and the data user;
(d) the transfer is necessary for the conclusion or performance of a contract, entered into at the request of the data subject, between the data user and a third party;
(e) the transfer is necessary for reasons of substantial public interest;
(f) the transfer is for the purpose of legal proceedings or prospective legal proceedings;
(g) the transfer is necessary to protect the vital interests of the data subject;
(h) the personal data is contained in a public register;
(i) the transfer is made pursuant to standard contractual clauses approved by the Commissioner;
(j) the transfer is made pursuant to binding corporate rules approved by the Commissioner;
(k) the transfer is made pursuant to a certification scheme approved by the Commissioner;
(l) the transfer is made pursuant to an international arrangement or agreement to which Malaysia is a party.
(3) The Commissioner shall publish and maintain a list of approved standard contractual clauses, binding corporate rules, and certification schemes for the purposes of this section.
(4) A data user who transfers personal data in contravention of this section commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable—
(a) to a fine not exceeding five hundred thousand ringgit;
(b) to imprisonment for a term not exceeding three years; or
(c) to both.

(1) A data user in a prescribed class of data users shall appoint a data protection officer.
(2) The data protection officer shall—
(a) inform and advise the data user and its employees of their obligations under this Act;
(b) monitor compliance with this Act and with applicable codes of practice;
(c) cooperate with the Commissioner and serve as the point of contact between the data user and the Commissioner;
(d) act as the contact point for data subjects in relation to matters relating to the processing of personal data;
(e) carry out such other functions as may be assigned by the data user or prescribed by regulations.
(3) The data user shall ensure that the data protection officer—
(a) is provided with sufficient resources to carry out the functions in subsection (2);
(b) has access to personal data and processing operations;
(c) is not given instructions that could lead to a conflict of interest.
(4) The data protection officer may be an employee of the data user or an external service provider.
(5) A data user who fails to appoint a data protection officer as required under this section commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding two hundred and fifty thousand ringgit or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding two years or to both.

(1) Any notice, order, or other document required or authorised to be served on or given to any person under this Act may be served—
(a) personally on that person;
(b) by leaving it at the usual or last known place of abode or business of that person;
(c) by registered post addressed to that person at his usual or last known place of abode or business;
(d) by electronic means to the email address registered with the Commissioner or to the electronic address provided by the data user in the registration application.
(2) Where a document is served by registered post, service shall be deemed to have been effected at the time at which the letter would be delivered in the ordinary course of post.
(3) Where service is effected by electronic means, service shall be deemed to have been effected at the time of successful transmission.

(1) The Minister may make regulations for or in respect of any matter required or permitted to be prescribed under this Act.
(2) Without limiting the generality of subsection (1), such regulations may—
(a) prescribe the classes of data users required to register;
(b) prescribe the forms of applications, notices, and certificates;
(c) prescribe fees payable under this Act;
(d) prescribe the manner of giving consent for the purposes of this Act;
(e) prescribe the form and manner of data breach notifications;
(f) prescribe the requirements for data protection officers;
(g) prescribe the requirements for data protection impact assessments;
(h) prescribe any other matter necessary or expedient for carrying out the purposes of this Act.
(3) Regulations under this section may create offences and prescribe penalties not exceeding those provided in this Act.

(1) A data user in a prescribed class of data users shall appoint a data protection officer.
(2) The data protection officer shall—
(a) inform and advise the data user and its employees of their obligations under this Act;
(b) monitor compliance with this Act and with applicable codes of practice;
(c) cooperate with the Commissioner and serve as the point of contact between the data user and the Commissioner;
(d) act as the contact point for data subjects in relation to matters relating to the processing of personal data;
(e) carry out such other functions as may be assigned by the data user or prescribed by regulations.
(3) The data user shall ensure that the data protection officer—
(a) is provided with sufficient resources to carry out the functions in subsection (2);
(b) has access to personal data and processing operations;
(c) is not given instructions that could lead to a conflict of interest.
(4) The data protection officer may be an employee of the data user or an external service provider.
(5) The details of the data protection officer shall be notified to the Commissioner and published in a manner accessible to data subjects.
(6) A data user who fails to appoint a data protection officer as required under this section commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding five hundred thousand ringgit.

(1) Where a type of processing is likely to result in a high risk to the rights and freedoms of data subjects, the data user shall, before the processing, carry out an assessment of the impact of the proposed processing operations on the protection of personal data (a 'data protection impact assessment').
(2) In determining whether processing is likely to result in a high risk, a data user shall have regard to—
(a) the use of new technologies;
(b) the nature, scope, context, and purposes of the processing;
(c) the sensitivity of the personal data to be processed;
(d) the volume and variety of personal data involved.
(3) The data user shall consult the Commissioner prior to processing where the impact assessment indicates that the processing would result in a high risk that cannot be mitigated.
(4) A data protection impact assessment shall contain—
(a) a description of the proposed processing operations and purposes;
(b) an assessment of the necessity and proportionality of the processing;
(c) an assessment of the risks to the rights and freedoms of data subjects;
(d) the measures envisaged to address the risks.
(5) A data user who fails to carry out a data protection impact assessment where required commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding five hundred thousand ringgit.

(1) A data user in a prescribed class shall maintain a record of processing activities carried out under the data user's responsibility.
(2) The record shall contain—
(a) the name and contact details of the data user and, where applicable, the data protection officer;
(b) the purposes of the processing;
(c) a description of the categories of data subjects and the categories of personal data processed;
(d) the categories of recipients to whom the personal data has been or will be disclosed;
(e) where applicable, transfers of personal data to a place outside Malaysia and the safeguards in place;
(f) the envisaged time limits for erasure of the different categories of personal data;
(g) a general description of the technical and organisational security measures implemented.
(3) Records maintained under this section shall be made available to the Commissioner on request.
(4) A data user who fails to maintain records as required commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable to a fine not exceeding three hundred thousand ringgit.

(1) The Commissioner shall, after consultation with the Advisory Committee, issue codes of practice as may be approved by the Minister for the guidance of data users.
(2) A code of practice may be issued in respect of any particular class of industry or activity.
(3) Where the Commissioner proposes to issue or revise a code of practice, the Commissioner shall—
(a) publish the proposed code or revision and invite public comments for a period of not less than thirty days;
(b) consider the comments received;
(c) submit the code or revision to the Advisory Committee for review;
(d) obtain the approval of the Minister before issuing.
(4) A code of practice is admissible as evidence in proceedings and shall be taken into account where relevant.

(1) Where a data user becomes aware of a data breach that results or is likely to result in significant harm to the data subjects concerned, the data user shall—
(a) notify the Commissioner of the data breach as soon as practicable but in any case not later than seventy-two hours after becoming aware of the data breach; and
(b) notify the data subjects who are affected by the data breach as soon as practicable.
(2) For the purposes of subsection (1), 'significant harm' includes—
(a) financial loss or gain that is unlawful;
(b) physical harm;
(c) significant emotional distress;
(d) damage to reputation;
(e) any other harm as may be prescribed by the Minister.
(3) The notification to the Commissioner under subsection (1)(a) shall contain—
(a) a description of the nature of the data breach including the categories and approximate number of data subjects concerned, and the categories and approximate number of personal data records concerned;
(b) the name and contact details of the data protection officer or other contact point where more information can be obtained;
(c) a description of the likely consequences of the data breach;
(d) a description of the measures taken or proposed to be taken to address the data breach, including, where appropriate, measures to mitigate its possible adverse effects.
(4) Where it is not possible to provide all required information at the time of the initial notification to the Commissioner, the data user may provide the information in phases, provided that subsequent notifications are made without undue delay.
(5) The notification to data subjects under subsection (1)(b) shall—
(a) describe in plain language the nature of the data breach;
(b) include the name and contact details of the data protection officer or other contact point;
(c) describe the likely consequences of the data breach;
(d) describe the measures taken or proposed to address the data breach and to mitigate its possible adverse effects;
(e) include recommendations for the data subject to mitigate potential harm.
(6) A data user may delay notification to data subjects if—
(a) notification would impede a criminal investigation; and
(b) law enforcement has requested such delay.
(7) The Commissioner may, at the request of the data user, extend the time period for notification under subsection (1)(a) if there are exceptional circumstances justifying the extension.
(8) A data user shall maintain a record of all data breaches, including those that do not require notification, and the reasons why notification was or was not made.
(9) A data user who fails to comply with this section commits an offence and shall, on conviction, be liable—
(a) to a fine not exceeding five hundred thousand ringgit;
(b) to imprisonment for a term not exceeding three years; or
(c) to both.

(1) The Minister may, by notification in the Gazette, exempt any person or class of persons or any processing of personal data or class of processing from all or any of the provisions of this Act.
(2) An exemption under this section may be given conditionally or unconditionally.
(3) The Minister shall, before granting an exemption under this section, consider the following:
(a) the nature and extent of the personal data being processed;
(b) the purpose for which the personal data is being processed;
(c) the harm that may be caused to data subjects;
(d) whether the exemption is in the public interest.

(1) Nothing in this Act shall affect—
(a) any right or obligation existing immediately before the commencement of this Act in respect of personal data processing by a person who was lawfully processing personal data at that time;
(b) any legal proceeding that has been commenced before the commencement of this Act;
(c) any investigation commenced before the commencement of this Act;
(d) any order, direction, or notice issued before the commencement of this Act.
(2) Any proceedings or investigation in respect of an offence or matter arising before the commencement of this Act may be continued and completed under the law applicable to such offence or matter as if this Act had not been enacted.
(3) Any right of appeal existing immediately before the commencement of this Act shall be exercised as if this Act had not been enacted.
